r\"}],[{\"indent\":\"-1\"},{\"indent\":\"+1\"}],[{\"header\":[1,2,3,4,5,6,false]}],[{\"color\":[]},{\"background\":[]}],[{\"align\":[]}],[\"clean\"]]},\"hidden_detail\":false,\"locked\":false,\"hidden_browse\":false,\"translation\":null,\"width\":\"full\",\"id\":\"170\",\"readonly\":false,\"group\":null,\"collection\":\"pages\",\"validation\":null}','{\"collection\":\"pages\",\"field\":\"content\",\"type\":\"string\",\"interface\":\"wysiwyg-full\",\"required\":true,\"sort\":null,\"note\":null,\"hidden_detail\":false,\"hidden_browse\":false,\"options\":{\"upload_files\":true,\"custom_url\":null,\"toolbarOptions\":[[\"bold\",\"italic\",\"underline\",\"strike\"],[\"blockquote\",\"code-block\"],[\"image\",\"choose-existing\"],[{\"header\":1},{\"header\":2}],[{\"list\":\"ordered\"},{\"list\":\"bullet\"}],[{\"script\":\"sub\"},{\"script\":\"super\"}],[{\"indent\":\"-1\"},{\"indent\":\"+1\"}],[{\"header\":[1,2,3,4,5,6,false]}],[{\"color\":[]},{\"background\":[]}],[{\"align\":[]}],[\"clean\"]]},\"id\":null,\"readonly\":false,\"validation\":null,\"width\":\"full\"}',NULL,NULL,NULL),(38,39,'pages','1','{\"name\":\"How to use\",\"id\":\"1\",\"subtitle\":\"How to use keygenes\",\"status\":\"draft\",\"content\":\"<h1>How to use KeyGenes<\\/h1><h2>1. Provided \\u201cfixed\\u201d training sets<\\/h2><p>KeyGenes has been developed and tested using NGS-derived human fetal transcriptional datasets as both training and test sets (Roost et al., 2015). The datasets used were expanded with available datasets on human adult tissues\\/organs (Cnop et al., 2014; Fagerberg et al., 2014; Illumina Body Map 2.0).<\\/p><p>It is worth mentioning, that NGS-derived data of more human adult organs\\/tissues are available (Fagerberg et al., 2014; Illumina Bodymap 2.0; Epigenomic Roadmap; ENCODE) and could be incorporated as the datasets to be used as training sets are flexible and expandable.<\\/p><p> We provide seven basic \\u201cfixed\\u201d training sets, which are supposed to give users a headstart to assign both identity and developmental stages to their differentiated cells (test set). How to create and use a \\u201cflexible\\u201d training set is described in section 2.<\\/p><h3>1. 1 Basic training sets<\\/h3><p>For a first and general assessment and before using a \\u201cflexible\\u201d training set, the following \\u201cfixed\\u201d training sets are recommended to determine identity:<\\/p><p>1. Fetal<\\/p><p> The training set \\u201cfetal\\u201d contains transcriptional signatures of 21x fetal organs\\/tissues and the maternal endometrium.<\\/p><p>2. Fetal wo<\\/p><p> The training set \\u201cfetal wo\\u201d contains transcriptional signatures of 17x fetal organs, excluding the extraembryonic organs\\/tissues and the maternal endometrium. Male and female gonads are taken together as gonad.<\\/p><h3>1.2. Staging training sets<\\/h3><p>For a basic assignment of a developmental stage to differentiated derivatives of pluripotent stem cells (PSCs), we provide the \\u201cfetal wo\\u201d training set now separated into first and second trimester and well as an adult training set. By comparing the outcomes using the three training sets, you can determine whether your sample is closer to a particular organ in the 1st trimester, 2nd trimester or adult:<\\/p><p>3. Fetal wo 1T<\\/p><p> The training set \\u201cfetal wo 1T\\u201d contains transcriptional signatures of 13x 1st trimester fetal, excluding the extraembryonic organs\\/tissues and the maternal endometrium.<\\/p><p>4. Fetal wo 2T<\\/p><p> The training set \\u201cfetal wo 2T\\u201d contains transcriptional signatures of 16x 2nd trimester fetal organs, excluding the extraembryonic organs\\/tissues and the maternal endometrium. Male and female gonad are taken together as gonad.<\\/p><p>5. Adult<\\/p><p> The training set \\u201cadult\\u201d contains transcriptional signatures of 11x fetal organs, excluding the extraembryonic organs\\/tissues and the cervix (Fagerberg et al., 2014; Illumina Bodymap 2.0). Ovaries and testes are taken together as gonads. With the heart samples, no distinction is made between atria and ventricles.<\\/p><h3>1.3 Other training sets<\\/h3><p>6. Fetal wo islets<\\/p><p> This training set includes the \\u201cfetal wo\\u201d training set expanded with five adult islet of Langerhans samples (Cnop et al., 2014). KeyGenes will split up the identity scores for pancreas into pancreas and adult islet. This training set has been tested on PSC-derived endocrine cells (Roost et al., 2015).<\\/p><p>7. Fetal wo islets 2<\\/p><p> This training set includes the \\u201cfetal wo\\u201d training set expanded with five adult islet of Langerhans samples (Cnop et al., 2014). KeyGenes will split up the identity scores for pancreas into 1T, 2T and adult islet. This training set has been tested on PSC-derived endocrine cells (Roost et al., 2015).<\\/p><h2>2. Web App<\\/h2><h3>2.1. Web App using the provided \\u201cfixed\\u201d training sets<\\/h3><p>The web app allows a prediction of NGS-derived data based on one of the \\u201cfixed\\u201d training sets described above in section 1.<\\/p><p>To run the KeyGenes Web App, follow the steps below:<\\/p><p>1. Fill in your email address in the first field, so you will get the results in your mailbox.<\\/p><p>2. Choose the \\u201cfixed\\u201d training set of interest from the dropdown menu.<\\/p><p>3. Upload the test set containing the raw reads.<\\/p><p> The provided training sets are based on Ensembl Gene IDs. Therefore, the test set must be in a specific tab-separated text file with genes (Ensembl Gene IDs, no duplicates) as rows and the queried samples as columns.<\\/p><p> The queried samples should be labelled as follows: sample_additional information (e.g. stomach_adult patient 1). To get a meaningful prediction of the queried samples, the tissue\\/cell type of interest must be represented in the training set.<\\/p><p>4. Press the submit button and check your mailbox for the results.<\\/p><h3>2.2. Web App using \\u201cflexible\\u201d training sets<\\/h3><p>We are currently working on the Web App to allow the use of flexible training sets.<\\/p><h2>3. The R-package<\\/h2><p>KeyGenes is made available as an R-package.<\\/p><h3>3.1 Installation<\\/h3><p>You can install the R-package by running the following command in R:<\\/p><p>devtools::install_github(\\u201cDavyCats\\/KeyGenes\\u201d, branch=\\u201dmaster\\u201d)<\\/p><h3>3.2 Usage<\\/h3><p>A vignette explaining the usage of the R-package can be found here: <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/davycats.github.io\\/KeyGenes\\/v0.1.html\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">https:\\/\\/davycats.github.io\\/KeyGenes\\/v0.1.html<\\/a><\\/p><p><strong>Click Here to show the documentation for the original (and obsolete) R scripts.<\\/strong><\\/p><h2>References:<\\/h2><p>Cnop, M., Abdulkarim, B., Bottu, G., Cunha, D.A., Igoillo-Esteve, M., Masini, M., Turatsinze, J.V., Griebel, T., Villate, O., Santin, I., et al. (2014). RNA sequencing identifies dysregulation of the human pancreatic islet transcriptome by the saturated fatty acid palmitate. Diabetes. 63(6): 1978-1993.<\\/p><p> Fagerberg, L., Hallstrom, B.M., Oksvold, P., Kampf, C., Djureinovic, D., Odeberg, J., Habuka, M., Tahmasebpoor, S., Danielsson, A., Edlund, K., et al. (2014). Analysis of the human tissue-specific expression by genome-wide integration of transcriptomics and antibody-based proteomics. Molecular &amp; cellular proteomics: MCP. 13(2): 397-406.<\\/p><p> Friedman J., Hastie T., and Tibshirani R. (2010). Regularization paths for generalized linear models via coordinate descent. Journal of statistical software. 33(1): 1-22.<\\/p><p> Roost M.S., van Iperen L., Ariyurek Y., Buermans H.P., Arindrarto W., Devalla H.D., Passier R., Mummery C.L., Carlotti F., de Koning E.J.P., van Zwet E.W., Goeman J.J., and Chuva de Sousa Lopes S.M. (2015). KeyGenes, a tool to probe tissue differentiation using a human fetal transcriptional atlas. Stem Cell Reports. 4(6):1112-24.<\\/p>\",\"sort\":null,\"created_by\":